{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.0.5"}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/oluwadarasimi99/google-capstone?scriptVersionId=94273408\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","outputs":[],"execution_count":0},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p id=\"part0\"></p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-family: Times New Roman; line-height: 2; font-size: 24px; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 2px; text-align: center; color: #FF8C00\"> CYCLISTICS DATA FROM MARCH 2021 - MARCH 2022</p>\n\n<img src=\"https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5311febee4b019c52e31c1b1/1538913977343-4EGTPNA60516BJ0FDBL1/Bike_Fall_Chicago.jpg?format=1500w\" width=\"100%\" align=\"center\" hspace=\"5%\" vspace=\"5%\"/>\n\n<p style=\"font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 20px; font-style: normal; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 3px; color: #808080; line-height:1.0\"> TABLE OF CONTENT</p>\n\n<p style=\"font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 2px; color: #808080; line-height:1.3\"><a href=\"#part1\" style=\"color:#808080\"> INTRODUCTION</a></p>\n\n<p style=\"font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 2px; color: #808080; line-height:1.3\"><a href=\"#part2\" style=\"color:#808080\">1 ASK</a></p>\n\n<p style=\"font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 2px; color: #808080; line-height:1.3\"><a href=\"#part3\" style=\"color:#808080\">2 PREPARE</a></p>\n\n\n<p style=\"font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 2px; color: #808080; line-height:1.3\"><a href=\"#part4\" style=\"color:#808080\">3 PROCESS</a></p>\n\n<p style=\"font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 2px; color: #808080; line-height:1.3\"><a href=\"#part5\" style=\"color:#808080\">4 ANALYSE</a></p>\n<p style=\"font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 2px; color: #808080; line-height:1.3\"><a href=\"#part6\" style=\"color:#808080\">5 SHARE</a></p>\n\n<p style=\"font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 2px; color: #808080; line-height:1.3\"><a href=\"#part7\" style=\"color:#808080\">6 ACT</a></p>\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"font-family: Arials; line-height: 1.5; font-size: 16px; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 2px; text-align: center; color: #008000\">Thanks for checking my notebook, I hope you find it interesting..</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">üòäüòäüòä</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p id=\"part1\"></p>\n<p style=\"font-family: Arials; font-size: 16px; font-style: bold; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 3px; color: #FF8C00\">INTRODUCTION</p>\n<hr style=\"height: 0.5px; border: 0; background-color: #808080\">\n\n\nThis is my project for the google data analytics capstone- Case study one which is about a cyclystic bike sharing company.The full documentation of this case study can be seen in the link below.\n\n<https://www.coursera.org/learn/google-data-analytics-capstone>\n\nThis project is essential so as to test the understanding of learners about the six data analytics process that was treated throughout the course which are\n* Ask\n* Prepare\n* Process\n* Analyse\n* Share\n* Act\n\n\n<p id=\"part2\"></p>\n<p style=\"font-family: Arials; font-size: 16px; font-style: bold; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 3px; color: #FF8C00\">ASK</p>\n<hr style=\"height: 0.5px; border: 0; background-color: #808080\">\n\n\nThis is the first phase of the data analytics process(ask questions to make data driven descision).\nin this case we will visit the documentation to get the proper context of our data.\n\n****Scenario****\n\nYou are a junior data analyst working in the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director\nof marketing believes the company‚Äôs future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore,\nyour team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently. From these insights,your team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.\n\n****Characters and teams****\n\n‚óè Cyclistic: A bike-share program that features more than 5,800 bicycles and 600 docking stations. Cyclistic sets itself apart by also offering reclining bikes, hand tricycles, and cargo bikes, making bike-share more inclusive to people with disabilities and riders who can‚Äôt use a standard two-wheeled bike. The majority of riders opt for traditional bikes; about 8% of riders use the assistive options. Cyclistic users are more likely to ride for leisure, but about 30% use them to\ncommute to work each day.\n\n‚óè Lily Moreno: The director of marketing and your manager. Moreno is responsible for the development of campaigns and initiatives to promote the bike-share program. These may include email, social media, and other channels.\n\n‚óè Cyclistic marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts who are responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that helps guide Cyclistic marketing strategy. You joined this team six months ago and have been busy learning about Cyclistic‚Äôs mission and business goals ‚Äî as well as how you, as a junior data analyst, can help Cyclistic achieve them.\n\n\n‚óè Cyclistic executive team: The notoriously detail-oriented executive team will decide whether to approve the\n\n\nGuiding questions\n\n‚óè What is the problem you are trying to solve?\n  \n  The company's future success has been said to be dependent on maximizing the anual membership holder and hence the problem here is our to get casual riders to become annual members.\n\n‚óè How can your insights drive business decisions?\n\nFrom the insights gotten, a new marketing strategy would be designed to convert casual riders to annual riders.\n\n***Key tasks***\n1. Identify the business task\n2. Consider key stakeholders\n\n***Deliverable***\nA clear statement of the business task\n\nTo better understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics.\n\n***Guiding Questions.***\n1. How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?\n2. Why would casual riders buy Cyclistic annual memberships?\n3. How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to become members?\n\n\n\n\n<p id=\"part3\"></p>\n<p style=\"font-family: Arials; font-size: 16px; font-style: bold; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 3px; color: #FF8C00\">PREPARE</p>\n<hr style=\"height: 0.5px; border: 0; background-color: #808080\">\n\n\nCyclistic‚Äôs historical trip data to analyze and identify trends and the datasets. The data has been made available by Motivate International Inc. and can be downloaded directly from kaggle [via this link](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kevinvenza/cyclistic-bike-share) \n\n**Guiding Questions**\n\n‚óè Where is your data located?\nThe dataset is located in kaggle [Through this link](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kevinvenza/cyclistic-bike-share) and can aslo be downloaded directly [from Divvy](https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html)\n\n‚óè How is the data organized?\n\nThe data is prepared by year and month and each of the months has its own CSV file.\n\n‚óè Are there issues with bias or credibility in this data? Does your data ROCCC?\n\nThere are no issues with bias and credibility as measures such as( removal of  trips that are taken by staff as they service and inspect the system; and any trips that were below 60 seconds in length (potentially false starts or users trying to re-dock a bike to ensure it was secure).) and yes the dataset is \n* reliable\n* original \n* comprehensive\n* current. \n* cited.\n\n‚óè How are you addressing licensing, privacy, security, and accessibility?\n\n The company has their own licence over the dataset and there are no personal or very sensitive information about the riders in the dataset also accessing the dataset is quite easy. To review the company's licence [Click here](https://ride.divvybikes.com/data-license-agreement)\n \n‚óè How did you verify the data‚Äôs integrity?\n\nThere are consistent namings for each columns and the data formats are correct for each column. Also null values are removed.\n\n‚óè How does it help you answer your question?\n\nNoticable trends about the casual and annual riders can help understand the behaviour\n\n‚óè Are there any problems with the data?\n\n***Key tasks***\n1. Download data and store it appropriately.\n2. Identify how it‚Äôs organized.\n3. Sort and filter the data.\n4. Determine the credibility of the data.\n\n***Deliverable***\n\nA description of all data sources used\n\nDivvy is Chicagoland‚Äôs bike share system across Chicago and Evanston. Divvy provides residents and visitors with a convenient, fun and affordable transportation option for getting around and exploring Chicago.\n\nDivvy, like other bike share systems, consists of a fleet of specially-designed, sturdy and durable bikes that are locked into a network of docking stations throughout the region. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system. People use bike share to explore Chicago, commute to work or school, run errands, get to appointments or social engagements, and more.\n\nDivvy is available for use 24 hours/day, 7 days/week, 365 days/year, and riders have access to all bikes and stations across the system.\n\n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#setting up R enviroment\n\nlibrary(tidyverse)\nlibrary(lubridate)\nlibrary(ggplot2)\nlibrary(dplyr)\nlibrary(geosphere)\nlibrary(janitor)\nlibrary(magrittr)\nlibrary(repr)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:07:14.007798Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:07:14.010225Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:07:15.481725Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"***Downloading dataset.....**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#Loading the datasets...\ncyclist_202103 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202103-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202104 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202104-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202105 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202105-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202106 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202106-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202107 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202107-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202108 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202108-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202109 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202109-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202110 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202110-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202111 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202111-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202112 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202112-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202201 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202201-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202202 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202202-divvy-tripdata.csv\")\ncyclist_202203 <- read.csv(\"../input/cyclistic-bike-sharing-march-2021-march-2022/202203-divvy-tripdata.csv\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:07:29.607812Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:07:29.664417Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:09:12.947322Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#checking for consistent column naming before performing merging datasets.\ncolnames(cyclist_202103)\ncolnames(cyclist_202104)\ncolnames(cyclist_202105)\ncolnames(cyclist_202106)\ncolnames(cyclist_202107)\ncolnames(cyclist_202108)\ncolnames(cyclist_202109)\ncolnames(cyclist_202110)\ncolnames(cyclist_202111)\ncolnames(cyclist_202112)\ncolnames(cyclist_202201)\ncolnames(cyclist_202202)\ncolnames(cyclist_202203)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:10:26.992446Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:10:26.993975Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:10:27.069414Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#Checking for incongruent dataset(i.e an inconsistent data set)\nstr(cyclist_202103)\nstr(cyclist_202104)\nstr(cyclist_202105)\nstr(cyclist_202106)\nstr(cyclist_202107)\nstr(cyclist_202108)\nstr(cyclist_202109)\nstr(cyclist_202110)\nstr(cyclist_202111)\nstr(cyclist_202112)\nstr(cyclist_202201)\nstr(cyclist_202202)\nstr(cyclist_202203)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:10:35.791381Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:10:35.793001Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:10:36.10525Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"font-family: Arials; font-size: 16px; font-style: bold; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 3px; color: #FF8C00\">PROCESS</p>\n<hr style=\"height: 0.5px; border: 0; background-color: #808080\">\n\n\nThis step prepares the data for analysis. All CSV files are merged together so as to aid the analysis process in this phase as well data cleaning is carried out to ensure a smooth and unbiased analysis. The tool being used for this project is Kaggle Markdown notebook, all codes are written in R programming language this is because R is an open source and easy programming language to use.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#merging all csv files together.\ncombined_cyclistics <- bind_rows(cyclist_202103, cyclist_202104, \n                                 cyclist_202105, cyclist_202106, \n                                 cyclist_202107, cyclist_202108, \n                                 cyclist_202109, cyclist_202110, \n                                 cyclist_202111, cyclist_202112, \n                                 cyclist_202201, cyclist_202202,cyclist_202203)\nhead(combined_cyclistics)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:10:45.61853Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:10:45.620324Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:10:55.682721Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#Inspecting the new and combined dataset(cyclistics_combined)\nglimpse(combined_cyclistics)\ncolnames(combined_cyclistics)\nnrow(combined_cyclistics)\ndim(combined_cyclistics)\nstr(combined_cyclistics)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:11:31.335164Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:11:31.336807Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:11:31.40435Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"\n\n#combined_cyclistics %>%\n#is.na()\n\n#inpsect each columns for count of missing values\nsapply(combined_cyclistics, function(x) sum(is.na(x))) \nmissing_rows<-unique (unlist (lapply (combined_cyclistics, function (x) which (is.na (x))))) \n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:11:45.70436Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:11:45.705933Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:11:59.779987Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#to drop all null or missing values\ncombined_cyclistics <- combined_cyclistics[c(-missing_rows),]\n\nsum(duplicated(combined_cyclistics))\n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:12:30.506808Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:12:30.508571Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:14:10.525895Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#To check for the total number of dropped rows due to null values or duplicate i.e(5952028 - 5947145 = 4,883  rows.)\ndim(combined_cyclistics)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:16:58.508471Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:16:58.510491Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:16:58.529418Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#to confirm all missing value or na for every column field.\nsapply(combined_cyclistics, function(x) sum(is.na(x))) ","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:17:08.926509Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:17:08.928045Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:17:18.85219Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#list all trip by adding new columns clearly stating date,day,month and year\ncombined_cyclistics$date <- as.Date(combined_cyclistics$started_at)\ncombined_cyclistics$month <- format(as.Date(combined_cyclistics$date), \"%B\")\ncombined_cyclistics$day <- format(as.Date(combined_cyclistics$date), \"%d\")\ncombined_cyclistics$year <- format(as.Date(combined_cyclistics$date), \"%Y\")\ncombined_cyclistics$day_of_week <- weekdays(combined_cyclistics$date)\ncombined_cyclistics$ride_duration <- difftime(combined_cyclistics$ended_at, combined_cyclistics$started_at)\ncombined_cyclistics$hour_of_day <- hour(combined_cyclistics$started_at)\n\n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:22:29.147929Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:22:29.14955Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:23:27.118071Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#A tibble showing  the added columns \nhead(combined_cyclistics)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:24:56.633087Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:24:56.6346Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:24:56.668939Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#showing the column names for combined_cyclistics\ncolnames(combined_cyclistics)\n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:25:04.95391Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:25:04.95553Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:25:04.973676Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#To check if there are  outliers in the column for hour_of_day(i.e was expected outcome(min? and max?) to be between 0.00 - 24 hours.)\nsummary(combined_cyclistics$hour_of_day)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:25:20.012403Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:25:20.014012Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:25:20.221985Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#Veryfying whether or not the lattitudes and longitude coordinates are useful for calculating distance of travel.\n#combined_cyclistics <- combined_cyclistics %>% \n    #rowwise() %>% \n        #mutate(distance = distHaversine(c(start_lng, start_lat), c(end_lng,end_lat)))\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#checking the result column for distance calculated from longitude and latitude.\ntibble(combined_cyclistics)\n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:25:29.021618Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:25:29.023093Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:25:29.207612Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#Ensuring that the data types are numeric\n\ncombined_cyclistics$ride_duration <- as.numeric(as.character(combined_cyclistics$ride_duration))\ncombined_cyclistics$hour_of_day <- as.numeric(as.character(combined_cyclistics$hour_of_day))\n\n\nhead(combined_cyclistics)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:25:40.753024Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:25:40.754571Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:25:48.911393Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#Filtering out ride_durations that are less than 0 and gettin the dimension of the remaining\ncombined_cyclistics <- filter(combined_cyclistics, ride_duration > 0)\ndim(combined_cyclistics)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:26:07.383975Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:26:07.385549Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:26:16.931062Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#write.table(combined_cyclistics,\n            #file = \".//combined_cylistics.csv\",\n            #row.names = F, sep=\",\"\n           \n           #)\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p id=\"part5\"></p>\n<p style=\"font-family: Arials; font-size: 16px; font-style: bold; font-weight: bold; letter-spacing: 3px; color: #FF8C00\">ANALYSE</p>\n<hr style=\"height: 0.5px; border: 0; background-color: #808080\">\n\n\nGuiding questions\n\n‚óè How should you organize your data to perform analysis on it?\n\nThe should be organized in a single csv file i.e merging all 13 datasets from march 2021 to march 2022\n\n‚óè Has your data been properly formatted?\n\nThe data as been properly formatted as the right naming covention and datatypes/formats has been ensured.\n\n‚óè What surprises did you discover in the data?\n\nThe suprise here is  despite the fact that member riders are more than the casual riders by 693550 i.e (3320012 - 2626462 = 693550 ), the average_duration_seconds for the casual rider is more than that of the member riders. This probably indicates that the distance travelled by casual riders is much longer or they travelled at shorter speed (The use of docked by by only casual riders which is assumed to travel at the smallest speed amongs the three types of bikes could also be a cause).\n\n‚óè What trends or relationships did you find in the data?\n\n1. One of the trends in the data was that member subscribers didnt use the docked bike and a few of casual users uses it.\n\n2. Also membership subscribers had most of there trips in the weekdays like(wednessday,tuesday,thursday,monday) and had less trips during the weekends.\n\n3. Casual users had most of there trips during the weekends unlike the membership subscribers.\n\n4. From the analysis the top 10 route for casual users and membership Subscribers was gotten\n\n\n‚óè How will these insights help answer your business questions?\n\nUnderstanding the casual users behaviour helps to take descicion that would encourage them to do member subscription\n\nKey tasks\n1. Aggregate your data so it‚Äôs useful and accessible.\n2. Organize and format your data.\n3. Perform calculations.\n4. Identify trends and relationships\n\n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"\ncolnames(combined_cyclistics)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2022-04-28T19:31:37.525898Z","iopub.execute_input":"2022-04-28T19:31:37.527425Z","iopub.status.idle":"2022-04-28T19:31:37.543018Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#filter data for member subscription only\nmember_only <- combined_cyclistics%>%\n    filter(member_casual == \"member\") %>%\n    select(ride_id, rideabl